We've reduced the problem to the following few lines. Fails both in .net core 2.2 and .Net Framework 4.7.2 (using C# language level 7.3). On Windows 10 Pro 64bit (1809).

**Code:**
```
static async Task Main(string[] args)
{
    Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");
    Foo(async () => throw new Exception("Oops"));
    Console.ReadLine();
}

static void Foo(Action action)
{
    Task.Run(action).ContinueWith(t =>
    {
       Console.WriteLine(t.Exception);
    }, TaskContinuationOptions.OnlyOnFaulted);
}
```
**Expected behavior:**
The task fails, and continues by writing the exception to the console. Then the application resumes normally.

**Actual behavior:**
The task fails and immediately crashes with an Unhandled Exception:

```
Unhandled Exception: System.Exception: Oops
   at ConsoleApp1.Program.<>c.<<Main>b__0_0>d.MoveNext() in D:\Projects\C#\ConsoleApp1\ConsoleApp1\Program.cs:line 12
--- End of stack trace from previous location where exception was thrown ---
   at System.Threading.ExecutionContext.RunInternal(ExecutionContext executionContext, ContextCallback callback, Object state)
--- End of stack trace from previous location where exception was thrown ---
   at System.Threading.ThreadPoolWorkQueue.Dispatch()
```
If we remove the ```async``` modifier on line 4 everything works as expected. If we change ```Action``` on line 8 to ```Func<Task>``` again everything works as expected.

